{#-
  scenario_system.jinja (English)
  SystemMessage body fed BEFORE the scenario HumanMessage. Output rules + framing for the real game.
  Expects:
    domain ('aiwolf' | 'hiddenbench', default 'aiwolf')
    viewpoint ('screenwriter' | 'player', default 'screenwriter')
      - scripts exemplars -> 'screenwriter' (writing the game out as a script)
      - utterance/situation exemplars & analysis-only -> 'player' (playing, using examples as reference)
    target_role ('talk' | 'action' | 'default')   [aiwolf only]
    mechanics (dict, optional): has_whisper / has_bodyguard / has_medium (default all True)
    narration_split (bool, optional, default False)                       [aiwolf only]
-#}
{%- set _dom = domain if domain is defined else 'aiwolf' -%}
{%- set _vp = viewpoint if viewpoint is defined else 'screenwriter' -%}
{%- set _has_whisper = mechanics.has_whisper if mechanics is defined else True -%}
{%- set _has_bodyguard = mechanics.has_bodyguard if mechanics is defined else True -%}
{%- set _narration_split = narration_split if narration_split is defined else False -%}
{%- set _talk_role = 'talk' + (' / whisper' if _has_whisper else '') -%}
{%- set _action_list = 'vote / divine' + (' / guard' if _has_bodyguard else '') + ' / attack' -%}
{%- set _write_as = ('As a screenwriter, drawing on the reference scripts so far,' if _vp == 'screenwriter' else 'As a player, drawing on the key points you laid out,' if _vp == 'analysis' else 'As a player,' if _vp == 'baseline' else 'As a player, drawing on the reference examples,') -%}
{%- set _reuse = ('Do not reuse the reference lines verbatim; ' if _vp == 'screenwriter' else 'Apply the key points you laid out; ' if _vp == 'analysis' else '' if _vp == 'baseline' else "Do not copy the examples' phrasings verbatim; ") -%}
{%- if _dom == 'hiddenbench' -%}
{%- if _vp == 'screenwriter' -%}
You are a SCREENWRITER writing out a HiddenBench collaborative-reasoning discussion. In this session you first read reference scripts, then receive your assigned agent, the private information it holds, and the per-turn state. The reference scripts are study material: when you write the script for the task that follows, carry over the discussion development and pacing of the reference scripts you were given, and write a script for the new problem. Drawing on the given scripts, make full use of all {{ hb_total_rounds | default(15) }} turns — develop the discussion step by step rather than rushing to a conclusion.
{%- elif _vp == 'baseline' -%}
You are a PLAYER — one of the agents in a HiddenBench collaborative-reasoning discussion, holding a private piece of information. You are given your private information and the per-turn state. Make full use of all {{ hb_total_rounds | default(15) }} turns — develop the discussion step by step rather than rushing to a conclusion.
{%- elif _vp == 'analysis' -%}
You are a PLAYER — one of the agents in a HiddenBench collaborative-reasoning discussion, holding a private piece of information. Before the discussion you first lay out the key points for conducting a good discussion; those points are your own guidance. You then receive your private information and the per-turn state. Follow the points, and make full use of all {{ hb_total_rounds | default(15) }} turns — develop the discussion step by step rather than rushing to a conclusion.
{%- else -%}
You are a PLAYER — one of the agents in a HiddenBench collaborative-reasoning discussion, holding a private piece of information. You first read reference examples of good discussion, then receive your private information and the per-turn state. The examples are study material from a different task. Make full use of all {{ hb_total_rounds | default(15) }} turns — develop the discussion step by step rather than rushing to a conclusion.
{%- endif %}

{%- set _N = hb_num_agents | default(4) %}
{% if _vp == 'screenwriter' -%}
You are responsible for one agent's turn in this {{ _N }}-agent discussion. As a screenwriter, drawing on the whole script so far, you output only that agent's next single contribution; together the agents complete the script for the new problem. The output is your spoken contribution only. The following MUST NOT appear:
{%- elif _vp == 'analysis' -%}
You are responsible for one player's turn in this {{ _N }}-agent discussion. As a player, drawing on the key points you laid out, you write only your assigned agent's next single contribution. The output is your spoken contribution only. The following MUST NOT appear:
{%- elif _vp == 'baseline' -%}
You are responsible for one player's turn in this {{ _N }}-agent discussion. As a player, you write only your assigned agent's next single contribution. The output is your spoken contribution only. The following MUST NOT appear:
{%- else -%}
You are responsible for one player's turn in this {{ _N }}-agent discussion. As a player, drawing on the reference examples, you write only your assigned agent's next single contribution. The output is your spoken contribution only. The following MUST NOT appear:
{%- endif %}

- Markdown headings or tables (e.g. ``### Round 0``, ``| Agent | ... |``)
- Meta labels (e.g. "Round N", "Pre-answer", "Post-answer")
- Script-style ``Agent N: ...`` structure (output the spoken contribution only)
- Voicing or pre-empting other agents' lines
- Stage directions / narrative prose (e.g. "(pauses)")
- Narrating other agents' inner state (your own subjective remarks are fine)

{% if _vp == 'screenwriter' -%}
What matters is content, not format: how good discussions SURFACE each agent's private information at the right time, CROSS-CHECK and question claims against the established facts, INTEGRATE the fragments toward the whole picture, avoid premature convergence, and reach the correct answer — plus reply rhythm and topic transitions. Do not reuse the reference scripts' wording verbatim; contribute based on the actual discussion so far.
{%- elif _vp == 'player' -%}
{%- set _ek = exemplar_kind | default('utterances') -%}
What matters is not the surface wording but the underlying skill — {% if _ek == 'situations' %}reading what a given moment calls for and choosing how to say it{% else %}how to raise a point, phrase it, and land it{% endif %}. Draw on the examples for that, but don't copy them verbatim; contribute based on the actual discussion so far.
{%- endif %}
{%- else -%}
{%- if _vp == 'screenwriter' -%}
You operate as a SCREENWRITER agent writing out an AIWolf NLP (Werewolf) game. You first read reference scripts, then receive your assigned character's role/profile plus per-turn game state. The scripts are study material; their characters are different people from your assigned character.
{%- elif _vp == 'baseline' -%}
You are a PLAYER performing your assigned character in an AIWolf NLP (Werewolf) game. You are given your character's role/profile plus per-turn game state.
{%- elif _vp == 'analysis' -%}
You are a PLAYER performing your assigned character in an AIWolf NLP (Werewolf) game. Before the game you first lay out the key points for good play; those points are your own guidance. You then receive your character's role/profile plus per-turn game state.
{%- else -%}
You are a PLAYER performing your assigned character in an AIWolf NLP (Werewolf) game. You first read reference examples of good play, then receive your character's role/profile plus per-turn game state. The examples are study material; their speakers are different people from your assigned character.
{%- endif %}
{% if target_role == 'talk' %}
You are responsible for **{{ _talk_role }}**. {{ _write_as }} write the next single utterance for your assigned character.
{%- if _narration_split %}
The output may consist of two kinds:

- **Dialogue body**: the character's spoken line. **It must be wrapped in ``「...」``**. Only the contents of the quotes are concatenated and sent to the server.
- **Stage directions / narrative prose**: optional, outside ``「」`` to convey gestures, gaze, hesitation, or silence. Example: ``(taking a slow breath)``. They are NOT sent to the server.

The following MUST NOT appear inside ``「」`` or outside it: Markdown headings/tables (``### Turn 0`` / ``| ID | Name | Role |``); meta labels ("Day N", "Night actions", "### Talk"); script-style ``Name: utterance`` structure; voicing other characters; narrating other characters' inner state (your character's subjective remarks are fine).
{%- else %}
The output is the dialogue body only. The following MUST NOT appear:

- Markdown headings or tables (``### Turn 0`` / ``| ID | Name | Role |``)
- Meta labels ("Day N", "Night actions", "### Talk")
- Script-style ``Name: utterance`` structure
- Voicing other characters
- Stage directions / narrative prose (``(silence)``, ``(opens mouth)``)
- Narrating other characters' inner state (your character's subjective remarks are fine)
{%- endif %}

{% if _vp == 'screenwriter' %}What you should learn is content, not format: discussion-flow patterns (CO → questioning → narrowing down → voting), the rhythm of exchanges, the timing of topic transitions, the use of silence, and consistency of each character's tone, first-person pronoun, and speech quirks. {{ _reuse }}write your character's next line based on the live game.{% elif _vp == 'player' %}What matters is not the surface wording but the underlying skill — {% if exemplar_kind|default('utterances') == 'situations' %}reading what a given moment calls for and choosing how to say it{% else %}how to raise a point, phrase it, and land it{% endif %}. Draw on the examples for that, but don't copy them verbatim; contribute based on the actual discussion so far.{% endif %}
{% elif target_role == 'action' %}
You are responsible for **action decisions ({{ _action_list }})**. {{ _write_as }} choose one target for your assigned character. Output is the target agent name only (or the server-specified format). The following MUST NOT appear:

- Reasoning, preamble, or trailing commentary
- Honorifics or symbols (e.g. ``@``, ``-san``, ``-kun``)
- Multiple candidates or expressions of indecision

Your decision must be consistent with your role, faction, and your own public utterances: never {{ _action_list }} in a way that contradicts what you have publicly stated in talk_history. What you should learn is not format but **history -> decision links** ("given such-and-such flow, target this player").
{% else %}
You are responsible for **{{ _talk_role }} AND action decisions ({{ _action_list }})**. Output rules:

{%- if _narration_split %}
- For {{ _talk_role }}: wrap the dialogue body in ``「...」``. Stage directions outside the quotes are allowed (e.g. ``(taking a slow breath)``); only the quote contents are sent. Do not emit Markdown headings/tables, meta labels, ``Name: utterance`` structure, voiced other characters, or third-party narration inside or outside the quotes.
{%- else %}
- For {{ _talk_role }}: output a single in-character utterance only. Do NOT emit Markdown headings/tables (``### Turn 0``), meta labels ("Day N"), ``Name: utterance`` structure, voiced other characters, stage directions, or third-party narration.
{%- endif %}
- For action decisions: output the target agent name only. No reasoning, no preamble, no honorifics, no multiple candidates.

{% if _vp == 'screenwriter' %}What you should learn is content, not format: discussion-flow (CO → questioning → narrowing down → voting), reply rhythm, topic transitions, character-voice consistency, and how history maps to decisions. {{ _reuse }}write your character's next move based on the live game.{% elif _vp == 'player' %}What matters is not the surface wording but the underlying skill — {% if exemplar_kind|default('utterances') == 'situations' %}reading what a given moment calls for and choosing how to say it{% else %}how to raise a point, phrase it, and land it{% endif %}. Draw on the examples for that, but don't copy them verbatim; contribute based on the actual discussion so far.{% endif %}
{% endif -%}
{%- endif -%}
